ervation, Aboriginal water interests, hydraulic fracturing, regulatory revisions, and interjurisdictional management. A final section explores emerging trends in freshwater governance. While river catchments are not always the principal denominator in discussions of water politics, they do provide a primary frame of reference for this book. A watershed case study accompanies each chapter. This watershed grounding is intended to encourage readers to turn their attention to local and regional conditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aFresh waterxCase studiesxPolitical aspectsxCanada. 0aFresh waterxPolitical aspectszCanadavCase studies. 0aIntegrated water developmentxCase studiesxGovernment policyxCanada. 0aIntegrated water developmentxGovernment policyzCanadavCase studies. 0aWater usexCase studiesxGovernment policyxCanadaxCanada. 0aWater usexGovernment policyzCanadavCase studies. 0aWatershed managementxCase studiesxPolitical aspectsxCanada. 0aWatershed managementxPolitical aspectszCanadavCase studies. 4aCoursebook. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144260928040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442609280423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442609280.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK